    {
      "id": "8f20b5209e154c87f616a0c2920bf93d10afe0b3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-12-07 17:36:19.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nHi Vitaly, as I mentioned in my previous comment, I'd like to follow a similar fix in LU-1259.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "2bf9ecdc629ec02f350cadf3fa8fbb7bac5cf51b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 135,
        "name": "Vitaly Fertman",
        "email": "vitaly.fertman@hpe.com",
        "username": "vitaly_fertman"
      },
      "date": "2012-12-07 18:38:19.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nHi! actually, I do not understand the objection. the previous patch was not complete as did not cover the 2nd callback. as the result you got LU-2317 and we can reproduce it as well, but with the current patch the issue is resolved. besides that, the way ORNL-27 was dropping the lock was not nice - instead of dropping the reference in the proper place, a comment was added that decref will be done in each individual callback and an extra protection is needed in each callback to not drop it twice... so, the current patch is more readable, has less LOCs, has no extra locking, so could be even considered as a cleanup. and the most important - fixes the issue.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "a21c43bacc33a3fee61de7784a9ce4380faffeaa",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-12-07 18:50:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nHi Vitaly, you may miss my first comment. Actually the way you do in the patch is exactly what I did in the first place that the notify thread requested and then released IR dlm lock.\n\nHowever, in the IR scalability testing where we had ~50K clients, I found that clients could hardly be granted with IR locks because there was a burst of enqueuing request so that the CPU was extremely busy. Therefore the notify thread couldn't be scheduled to release the lock for quite a long time. This issue was fixed by:\n1. cancel IR lock on completion ast\n2. raise the thread priority of notify thread\n\nBased on the factor that there is no such scalable environment to verify this patch, I'm reluctant to do it this way.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "8360e7dca4e96b311e3774267ce98e8ca0360340",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 135,
        "name": "Vitaly Fertman",
